WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.440
[Amit Varma]: We are born communicating with other people, so you'd think communication would be easy

00:00:10.440 --> 00:00:12.280
[Amit Varma]: and intuitive for us, right?

00:00:12.280 --> 00:00:16.280
[Amit Varma]: Our first cry on this earth, in fact, is a form of communication.

00:00:16.280 --> 00:00:21.680
[Amit Varma]: And we go through our lives as social animals, learning by interacting with others.

00:00:21.680 --> 00:00:26.880
[Amit Varma]: And yet, so often, whatever else we succeed at, we fail at communicating.

00:00:26.880 --> 00:00:32.440
[Amit Varma]: And this failure harms every area of our lives, from our relationships to our careers to our

00:00:32.440 --> 00:00:34.400
[Amit Varma]: own intellectual growth.

00:00:34.400 --> 00:00:39.640
[Amit Varma]: I got a sense of the importance of communication in general, and conversations in particular,

00:00:39.640 --> 00:00:42.000
[Amit Varma]: when I started The Seen and The Unseen.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:47.200
[Amit Varma]: As I learned the craft, one of the rules I drew for myself was that I had to listen more

00:00:47.200 --> 00:00:52.400
[Amit Varma]: than talk, actually pay attention to the people I was speaking with, and keep my own sense

00:00:52.400 --> 00:00:54.960
[Amit Varma]: of ego out of the conversation.

00:00:54.960 --> 00:00:59.520
[Amit Varma]: Good conversation isn't about showing off how much you know, how smart you are, or even

00:00:59.520 --> 00:01:00.680
[Amit Varma]: winning an argument.

00:01:00.680 --> 00:01:04.400
[Amit Varma]: The interesting thing is that there are so few interview shows around that actually share

00:01:04.400 --> 00:01:05.880
[Amit Varma]: this philosophy.

00:01:05.880 --> 00:01:10.120
[Amit Varma]: Interview shows, especially on TV, are often full of hosts interrupting their guests all

00:01:10.120 --> 00:01:13.480
[Amit Varma]: the time, which makes for choppy, shallow conversation.

00:01:13.480 --> 00:01:17.760
[Amit Varma]: And their main purpose often isn't to gain insight from the guest, but to catch them

00:01:17.760 --> 00:01:21.960
[Amit Varma]: in a gotcha moment, so they can show off their own superior intellect.

00:01:21.960 --> 00:01:24.600
[Amit Varma]: This is both rude and toxic.

00:01:24.600 --> 00:01:28.760
[Amit Varma]: Every single person on this planet knows something that we don't.

00:01:28.760 --> 00:01:33.000
[Amit Varma]: Every conversation gives us a chance to expand our universe.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:39.080
[Amit Varma]: And that is why, when we are in a conversation, our focus should not be on how we talk, but

00:01:39.080 --> 00:01:40.080
[Amit Varma]: on how we listen.

00:01:40.080 --> 00:01:49.160
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics, and behavioral

00:01:49.160 --> 00:01:50.160
[Unknown]: science.

00:01:50.160 --> 00:01:55.800
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Varma.

00:01:55.800 --> 00:01:56.960
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen.

00:01:56.960 --> 00:02:01.760
[Amit Varma]: I've been thinking for months that I should ask Russ Roberts on my show, but I hesitated

00:02:01.760 --> 00:02:03.960
[Amit Varma]: because it felt almost audacious.

00:02:03.960 --> 00:02:08.760
[Amit Varma]: Russ is the ultimate master of what I try to do, have deep conversations with people

00:02:08.760 --> 00:02:11.480
[Amit Varma]: that expand our brains and our sense of the world.

00:02:11.480 --> 00:02:18.240
[Amit Varma]: His podcast, Econ Talk, began in 2006, and he has had more than 700 amazing conversations

00:02:18.240 --> 00:02:19.480
[Amit Varma]: on it since then.

00:02:19.480 --> 00:02:23.640
[Amit Varma]: It's a marvelous show that's, over the years, not only given me great insights on economics

00:02:23.640 --> 00:02:29.520
[Amit Varma]: and politics, but has also shown me the craft of how to have a conversation.

00:02:29.520 --> 00:02:34.360
[Amit Varma]: Besides being the original podcaster, Russ has also been an economics educator.

00:02:34.360 --> 00:02:39.200
[Amit Varma]: I first came across him a decade and a half ago through Cafe Hayek, the brilliant blog

00:02:39.200 --> 00:02:40.940
[Amit Varma]: he co-wrote with Don Boudreau.

00:02:40.940 --> 00:02:45.900
[Amit Varma]: He has written a bunch of brilliant books as well, and has been a guiding light to generations

00:02:45.900 --> 00:02:49.440
[Amit Varma]: of people learning about economics and the world around us.

00:02:49.440 --> 00:02:54.640
[Amit Varma]: So I finally gathered up the courage to invite him on my show and was delighted when he agreed.

00:02:54.640 --> 00:02:59.240
[Amit Varma]: What you're about to hear now is a wide ranging conversation across subjects.

00:02:59.240 --> 00:03:04.760
[Amit Varma]: The art of conversation, the nature of morality, our changing political discourse, and yes,

00:03:04.760 --> 00:03:05.960
[Amit Varma]: some economics as well.

00:03:05.960 --> 00:03:10.240
[Amit Varma]: I've had trouble thinking of a title for this episode, in fact, because we covered so much

00:03:10.240 --> 00:03:11.240
[Amit Varma]: ground.

00:03:11.240 --> 00:03:15.980
[Amit Varma]: This was one of the conversations that I have most enjoyed on The Seen and The Unseen.

00:03:15.980 --> 00:03:20.200
[Amit Varma]: But before we get started, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:03:20.200 --> 00:03:24.160
[Amit Varma]: Hi, I'm Vivek Kaul.

00:03:24.160 --> 00:03:28.200
[Amit Varma]: And I'm Amit Verma, here to tell you about a new weekly podcast that Vivek and I have

00:03:28.200 --> 00:03:30.720
[Amit Varma]: launched called Econ Central.

00:03:30.720 --> 00:03:36.680
[Unknown]: In Econ Central, we will help you make sense of the economic news of the last week.

00:03:36.680 --> 00:03:40.520
[Unknown]: And we'll also try to explain complex subjects in a simple language.

00:03:40.520 --> 00:03:45.520
[Amit Varma]: We will also take events outside the world of economics, like from politics, sports,

00:03:45.520 --> 00:03:49.920
[Amit Varma]: literature, and explain them through the lens of economic thinking.

00:03:49.920 --> 00:03:53.600
[Unknown]: Why is the stock market going up when the economy is going down?

00:03:53.600 --> 00:03:55.920
[Unknown]: What's the deal with high petrol prices?

00:03:55.920 --> 00:03:57.880
[Amit Varma]: Should we boycott Chinese goods?

00:03:57.880 --> 00:04:00.680
[Amit Varma]: What does free speech have to do with incentives?

00:04:00.680 --> 00:04:04.520
[Amit Varma]: Why are the roving bandits of Uttar Pradesh in competition with the biggest protection

00:04:04.520 --> 00:04:07.040
[Unknown]: racket out there, the Indian state?

00:04:07.040 --> 00:04:10.880
[Unknown]: All this and more in our new weekly podcast, Econ Central.

00:04:10.880 --> 00:04:15.960
[Amit Varma]: Econ Central launched a few weeks ago, and is free on all podcast apps, you can browse

00:04:15.960 --> 00:04:20.400
[Amit Varma]: our archives at econcentral.in.

00:04:20.400 --> 00:04:24.160
[Unknown]: Econ Central, you have an incentive to listen.

00:04:24.160 --> 00:04:26.600
[Amit Varma]: Don't forget the URL, econcentral.in.

00:04:26.600 --> 00:04:34.440
[Amit Varma]: Russ, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:04:34.440 --> 00:04:35.440
[Guest]: Great to be with you, Amit.

00:04:35.440 --> 00:04:40.360
[Amit Varma]: Russ, it's a great pleasure to have you on the show because not only are you, you know,

00:04:40.360 --> 00:04:44.880
[Amit Varma]: the writers I used to read very seriously a decade and a half ago, for your insights

00:04:44.880 --> 00:04:47.200
[Amit Varma]: on economics, but you're also one of the early podcasters.

00:04:47.200 --> 00:04:51.440
[Amit Varma]: In fact, so early that at that time, I didn't really take podcasting very seriously.

00:04:51.440 --> 00:04:56.080
[Amit Varma]: But yours, Econ Talk was the one podcast, which, you know, just captivated me for the

00:04:56.080 --> 00:04:59.080
[Amit Varma]: incredible range of guests and conversations that you've had.

00:04:59.080 --> 00:05:02.680
[Amit Varma]: And you've done more than 700 episodes of that, which is, you know, I've just done like

00:05:02.680 --> 00:05:04.360
[Amit Varma]: this is episode 182.

00:05:04.360 --> 00:05:06.080
[Amit Varma]: So it sounds a bit daunting.

00:05:06.080 --> 00:05:12.600
[Amit Varma]: I want to take you a bit further back and sort of ask you about your intellectual journey

00:05:12.600 --> 00:05:17.800
[Amit Varma]: from the time you kind of started and became a student and got interested in economics.

00:05:17.800 --> 00:05:23.160
[Amit Varma]: Why economics and sort of who shaped your views of the world, who were the thinkers

00:05:23.160 --> 00:05:25.000
[Guest]: who influenced you and so on.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:26.440
[Guest]: So we could go as deep as you want.

00:05:26.440 --> 00:05:30.720
[Guest]: You'll steer me maybe and give me some suggestions on where you want to head with that.

00:05:30.720 --> 00:05:35.200
[Guest]: But the simple starting point is that I was good at economics.

00:05:35.200 --> 00:05:36.200
[Guest]: I enjoyed it.

00:05:36.200 --> 00:05:44.720
[Guest]: I saw it as a puzzle to be solved the way that the theory fit together of consumers

00:05:44.720 --> 00:05:49.680
[Guest]: and producers yielding prices and quantities in the marketplace.

00:05:49.680 --> 00:05:53.640
[Guest]: I found that kind of beautiful and satisfying intellectually.

00:05:53.640 --> 00:05:58.760
[Guest]: And then I saw that it was a way to think about how to make the world better.

00:05:58.760 --> 00:06:03.960
[Guest]: A vision that I've now become much more skeptical of, but when I was younger, it appealed to

00:06:03.960 --> 00:06:08.840
[Guest]: me deeply, this idea that we can help make people's lives better through economic policy.

00:06:08.840 --> 00:06:12.800
[Guest]: We can improve certain policies, get rid of others, add new ones.

00:06:12.800 --> 00:06:18.960
[Guest]: And in theory, encourage opportunities for people to grow financially as well as in other

00:06:18.960 --> 00:06:19.960
[Guest]: ways.

00:06:19.960 --> 00:06:25.360
[Guest]: I saw it as a way to think about what kind of country and where we want to live in in

00:06:25.360 --> 00:06:31.280
[Guest]: terms of structure, capitalism versus socialism, free markets versus command and control.

00:06:31.280 --> 00:06:32.840
[Guest]: So all of that was very captivating to me.

00:06:32.840 --> 00:06:37.720
[Guest]: And the intellectual influences in those early days, I was much more libertarian, I think,

00:06:37.720 --> 00:06:38.720
[Guest]: than I am now.

00:06:38.720 --> 00:06:42.000
[Guest]: I'm still pretty libertarian, but I was more of an ideologue than I am now.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:47.240
[Guest]: I was very influenced by Milton Friedman, Robert Nozick.

00:06:47.240 --> 00:06:54.280
[Guest]: Those are the two, I would say, big influences of my youngest, and Ayn Rand, who I'm not

00:06:54.280 --> 00:06:57.480
[Guest]: as nearly as fond of now as I was when I was a teenager.

00:06:57.480 --> 00:07:02.360
[Guest]: But those are people that got me interested in this idea of liberty, of freedom, and particularly

00:07:02.360 --> 00:07:06.680
[Guest]: of economic policy that would allow that freedom.

00:07:06.680 --> 00:07:12.600
[Guest]: And that was, you know, I went off to graduate school and found a new set of mentors and

00:07:12.600 --> 00:07:19.200
[Guest]: intellectual mentors, people like Gary Becker, Deirdre McCloskey, George Stigler, Sam Peltzman.

00:07:19.200 --> 00:07:25.960
[Guest]: These are people who affected how I viewed economics, how I viewed politics.

00:07:25.960 --> 00:07:34.480
[Guest]: And then, interestingly for me, maybe of interest to you, but in 2003, I joined the faculty

00:07:34.480 --> 00:07:36.080
[Guest]: George Mason.

00:07:36.080 --> 00:07:41.280
[Guest]: And at that point, I started getting very interested in the ideas of Hayek, the great

00:07:41.280 --> 00:07:44.760
[Guest]: Austrian economist, Nobel laureate.

00:07:44.760 --> 00:07:50.760
[Guest]: And I spent a lot of the next years thinking about the idea of emergent order, the idea

00:07:50.760 --> 00:07:58.600
[Guest]: of complexity, and how individual choices get magnified and aggregated into outcomes.

00:07:58.600 --> 00:08:05.240
[Guest]: And that was another big influence, you know, people like Don Boudreau there, I learned

00:08:05.240 --> 00:08:10.960
[Guest]: an immense amount from him about economics that I just hadn't thought about enough in

00:08:10.960 --> 00:08:13.040
[Guest]: different ways.

00:08:13.040 --> 00:08:16.440
[Guest]: And I had many, many colleagues there who influenced me.

00:08:16.440 --> 00:08:24.600
[Guest]: But the real change was that in 2006, as you pointed out, back in the Pleistocene era,

00:08:24.600 --> 00:08:27.400
[Guest]: I started EconTalk.

00:08:27.400 --> 00:08:32.640
[Guest]: And originally, EconTalk was me talking for an hour with an economist who either I knew

00:08:32.640 --> 00:08:36.120
[Guest]: or I could talk into coming on the program in the early days.

00:08:36.120 --> 00:08:39.480
[Guest]: As you know, when you're getting started, it's a little challenging, and if you build

00:08:39.480 --> 00:08:42.320
[Guest]: up a guest list, it gets easier.

00:08:42.320 --> 00:08:47.440
[Guest]: And I started to talk to my, you know, former professors and other people who were doing

00:08:47.440 --> 00:08:49.120
[Guest]: interesting work.

00:08:49.120 --> 00:08:59.840
[Guest]: And that forced an immense broadening of my horizons, first to be aware of the fallibility

00:08:59.840 --> 00:09:01.120
[Guest]: of my viewpoint.

00:09:01.120 --> 00:09:05.480
[Guest]: I didn't turn against my viewpoint, but I realized that the viewpoint that I had, I

00:09:05.480 --> 00:09:10.000
[Guest]: realized that a lot of the reasons that I thought it was the right way to think about

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:13.160
[Guest]: the world weren't really the reasons that I adopted that viewpoint.

00:09:13.160 --> 00:09:18.160
[Guest]: I assumed, you know, I just assumed I had all the best studies, all the right studies,

00:09:18.160 --> 00:09:19.160
[Guest]: all the good facts.

00:09:19.160 --> 00:09:21.120
[Guest]: The other side, they were just wrong.

00:09:21.120 --> 00:09:25.200
[Guest]: And at some point, probably after interviewing Robert Frank, who looks at the world differently

00:09:25.200 --> 00:09:29.320
[Guest]: than I do, and other people, I started to realize that, you know, this sounds kind of

00:09:29.320 --> 00:09:30.320
[Guest]: – this is embarrassing.

00:09:30.320 --> 00:09:32.360
[Guest]: It sounds kind of childish and naive.

00:09:32.360 --> 00:09:36.320
[Guest]: But I started to become aware of my own confirmation bias.

00:09:36.320 --> 00:09:43.880
[Guest]: And I was reading Nassim Nicholas Taleb at the time, his book Fooled by Randomness.

00:09:43.880 --> 00:09:52.440
[Guest]: And that set me on a path of a very different intellectual arc of exploring uncertainty,

00:09:52.440 --> 00:09:56.200
[Guest]: overconfidence, humility.

00:09:56.200 --> 00:09:59.920
[Guest]: And similarly – and I'm almost done with this travelogue – and similarly, I started

00:09:59.920 --> 00:10:05.360
[Guest]: – I had a set of conversations with Dan Klein, my colleague at George Mason on Adam

00:10:05.360 --> 00:10:09.240
[Guest]: Smith and his book, The Theory of Moral Sentiments.

00:10:09.240 --> 00:10:14.680
[Guest]: And that was another complication to my worldview because, you know, Smith is thought of as

00:10:14.680 --> 00:10:21.760
[Guest]: this free market economist who wrote The Wealth of Nations, which of course he is.

00:10:21.760 --> 00:10:25.360
[Guest]: But he also has this other book, The Theory of Moral Sentiments, where he's very interested

00:10:25.360 --> 00:10:32.000
[Guest]: in our moral sympathies and the fact that we sometimes act altruistically and what's

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:33.720
[Guest]: the source of happiness.

00:10:33.720 --> 00:10:42.600
[Guest]: And I started to really open up my mind to the richness of philosophy and saw my past

00:10:42.600 --> 00:10:48.080
[Guest]: training in economics as just a little bit sterile, a little bit too narrow.

00:10:48.080 --> 00:10:50.600
[Guest]: So in a way, I haven't changed much at all.

00:10:50.600 --> 00:10:55.160
[Guest]: The things I care about, the principles I stand for, they're pretty much the same.

00:10:55.160 --> 00:11:00.480
[Guest]: I just have a different way of thinking about them and a willingness to realize that the

00:11:00.480 --> 00:11:05.120
[Guest]: world is not as open and shut as I probably thought when I was 30 years old.

00:11:05.120 --> 00:11:09.320
[Guest]: And so that's really the – that's a quick look at what I've been – how my thinking

00:11:09.320 --> 00:11:10.720
[Guest]: has changed over time.

00:11:10.720 --> 00:11:16.080
[Guest]: I'm increasingly interested in philosophy, and philosophy is about asking good questions,

00:11:16.080 --> 00:11:17.080
[Guest]: not about answers.

00:11:17.080 --> 00:11:20.960
[Guest]: I'm increasingly interested in risk and uncertainty, too.

00:11:20.960 --> 00:11:28.040
[Guest]: I'm always struck by how subtle and challenging it is to think about those topics thoughtfully.

00:11:28.040 --> 00:11:31.400
[Guest]: The people who are very confident in themselves in those areas are dangerous.

00:11:31.400 --> 00:11:34.440
[Guest]: It really is important to know what you don't know.

00:11:34.440 --> 00:11:42.320
[Guest]: So that's what I'm interested in, and at the same time, the country I live in has gone

00:11:42.320 --> 00:11:47.280
[Guest]: off the rails, become unmoored, discourse has been degraded.

00:11:47.280 --> 00:11:50.320
[Guest]: So I've been increasingly interested in trying to understand how that happened.

00:11:50.320 --> 00:11:53.560
[Guest]: What is going – and it's not only in America, of course.

00:11:53.560 --> 00:12:00.200
[Guest]: The rise of populism, the really rearrangement of what is considered left and right, what's

00:12:00.200 --> 00:12:05.720
[Guest]: considered sort of mainstream liberal-conservative differences, I'm very interested in how that

00:12:05.720 --> 00:12:07.280
[Guest]: has come to pass.

00:12:07.280 --> 00:12:13.320
[Guest]: So that's another set of interviews and topics and reading I'm doing to try to wrap my head

00:12:13.320 --> 00:12:14.320
[Guest]: around that.

00:12:14.320 --> 00:12:20.120
[Amit Varma]: There are a lot of threads I want to pick from what you just spoke about and kind of

00:12:20.120 --> 00:12:21.120
[Amit Varma]: unpack them.

00:12:21.120 --> 00:12:25.120
[Amit Varma]: But the first one I look at is, you know, I just finished rereading your book, How Adam

00:12:25.120 --> 00:12:29.400
[Amit Varma]: Smith Can Change Your Life, which is, of course, quotes a lot from a theory of moral sentiments.

00:12:29.400 --> 00:12:33.280
[Amit Varma]: And one of the first things that strikes you there, of course, is that, you know, we can

00:12:33.280 --> 00:12:38.320
[Amit Varma]: post-facto, we can think of Smith as an economist, but he was also a moral philosopher.

00:12:38.320 --> 00:12:40.140
[Amit Varma]: He was also a political philosopher.

00:12:40.140 --> 00:12:45.600
[Amit Varma]: He was also an economist, of course, I mean, practically the founder of modern economics.

00:12:45.600 --> 00:12:49.080
[Amit Varma]: And similarly, when I was looking at the sort of people you studied with and worked with,

00:12:49.080 --> 00:12:54.440
[Amit Varma]: like Gary Becker, who strikes me almost as a quintessential 19th century intellectual

00:12:54.440 --> 00:12:57.920
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that his interests are so wide ranging.

00:12:57.920 --> 00:13:01.720
[Amit Varma]: He has, you know, studied and written on so many different subjects.

00:13:01.720 --> 00:13:06.260
[Amit Varma]: Whereas, if you look at the modern time, my impression of it is that everyone is expected

00:13:06.260 --> 00:13:07.780
[Amit Varma]: to be a specialist.

00:13:07.780 --> 00:13:12.440
[Amit Varma]: You don't have an economist talking about moral philosophy or vice versa.

00:13:12.440 --> 00:13:18.720
[Amit Varma]: And how much do you feel that that's a trap for people who are in academics today or maybe

00:13:18.720 --> 00:13:23.520
[Amit Varma]: over the last few decades that you tend to increasingly specialize and how important

00:13:23.520 --> 00:13:29.240
[Amit Varma]: it is to then do that kind of wide ranging thinking and studying, which, in a sense,

00:13:29.240 --> 00:13:32.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, you were forced to do by the nature of the conversations you had to have on EconTalk

00:13:32.920 --> 00:13:35.320
[Amit Varma]: because you're talking to so many disparate people.

00:13:35.320 --> 00:13:37.800
[Amit Varma]: But how important is that?

00:13:37.800 --> 00:13:39.960
[Guest]: And is it a rare thing?

00:13:39.960 --> 00:13:42.480
[Guest]: So that's a really interesting question.

00:13:42.480 --> 00:13:48.440
[Guest]: I've actually started thinking about aspects of that in the last year or so because I think

00:13:48.440 --> 00:13:54.040
[Guest]: a lot about what's happened to my discipline over the last 30, 40 years, economics.

00:13:54.040 --> 00:13:59.000
[Guest]: When I was being trained and in the decade or so after I came out into the job market

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:07.040
[Guest]: and became an academic, the emphasis was on very high powered mathematics.

00:14:07.040 --> 00:14:13.560
[Guest]: The people who were respected and had prestige were the people who could use the most advanced

00:14:13.560 --> 00:14:15.320
[Guest]: mathematics.

00:14:15.320 --> 00:14:16.320
[Guest]: That's changed.

00:14:16.320 --> 00:14:20.320
[Guest]: Today, the people who are most respected in economics are the people who can do the most

00:14:20.320 --> 00:14:26.400
[Guest]: sophisticated statistical techniques to manipulate data and try to understand it.

00:14:26.400 --> 00:14:28.880
[Guest]: And both of those are interesting.

00:14:28.880 --> 00:14:35.080
[Guest]: But what I've come to realize and to think about your question in terms of specialization,

00:14:35.080 --> 00:14:39.920
[Guest]: there's a really funny kind of specialization that I think is the most important one.

00:14:39.920 --> 00:14:42.360
[Guest]: First, let me react to what you said about Gary Becker.

00:14:42.360 --> 00:14:45.400
[Guest]: Gary Becker had, as you said, had incredibly wide ranging interests.

00:14:45.400 --> 00:14:46.400
[Guest]: He wrote on the family.

00:14:46.400 --> 00:14:49.900
[Guest]: He wrote on crime, wrote on discrimination.

00:14:49.900 --> 00:14:56.480
[Guest]: He was the ultimate economic imperialist on politics, of course, also.

00:14:56.480 --> 00:15:00.600
[Guest]: He was trying to use the tools of economics to understand all those things.

00:15:00.600 --> 00:15:04.240
[Guest]: So in one sense, he was incredibly diverse.

00:15:04.240 --> 00:15:09.240
[Guest]: In other sense, he was incredibly narrow because he forced every one of those areas into the

00:15:09.240 --> 00:15:10.600
[Guest]: economic lens.

00:15:10.600 --> 00:15:13.720
[Guest]: And let's digress for a minute and talk about what that economic lens is.

00:15:13.720 --> 00:15:23.520
[Guest]: That economic lens is the idea that rationality, the right behavior, is to maximize something

00:15:23.520 --> 00:15:27.360
[Guest]: subject to the constraints of your situation.

00:15:27.360 --> 00:15:31.520
[Guest]: So the simplest way to think about this in economics is the economist's view of human

00:15:31.520 --> 00:15:39.600
[Guest]: behavior is that we try to get the maximum satisfaction out of life, given that we don't

00:15:39.600 --> 00:15:42.320
[Guest]: have an infinite amount of money.

00:15:42.320 --> 00:15:45.120
[Guest]: Now, that's a really powerful tool, as it turns out.

00:15:45.120 --> 00:15:48.640
[Guest]: In a way, it's kind of it's almost a tautology.

00:15:48.640 --> 00:15:50.960
[Guest]: It's almost not so interesting by itself.

00:15:50.960 --> 00:15:57.040
[Guest]: But economists take that tool, and Gary Becker was the master of it, and use it to see what

00:15:57.040 --> 00:16:01.840
[Guest]: insights they can get or what predictions they can get about human behavior.

00:16:01.840 --> 00:16:06.240
[Guest]: So just to take one crazy one that part of the reason Gary Becker got a Nobel Prize is

00:16:06.240 --> 00:16:11.080
[Guest]: that he said, let's treat the decision to have children the way we treat every other

00:16:11.080 --> 00:16:12.640
[Guest]: decision.

00:16:12.640 --> 00:16:18.440
[Guest]: We have children because we enjoy them, and then we invest in them.

00:16:18.440 --> 00:16:23.240
[Guest]: We give them knowledge, time, and then they go out into the world.

00:16:23.240 --> 00:16:27.760
[Guest]: They might, in a primitive society, be a literal investment.

00:16:27.760 --> 00:16:31.880
[Guest]: They might end up taking care of me or working on my farm or taking care of me in my old

00:16:31.880 --> 00:16:32.880
[Guest]: age.

00:16:32.880 --> 00:16:36.960
[Guest]: In modern times, the investment is more to turn them into a kind of person I'm going

00:16:36.960 --> 00:16:37.960
[Guest]: to like.

00:16:37.960 --> 00:16:40.720
[Guest]: That would be one way to think about child raising.

00:16:40.720 --> 00:16:46.480
[Guest]: And what Becker talks about is the trade-off between quantity and quality of children.

00:16:46.480 --> 00:16:49.120
[Guest]: Now, this offends people tremendously.

00:16:49.120 --> 00:16:52.400
[Guest]: It offends me a little bit now, but I want to be clear with the nature of the offenses.

00:16:52.400 --> 00:17:00.840
[Guest]: So what he meant by that was if you want to have children of a certain ability and have

00:17:00.840 --> 00:17:04.480
[Guest]: them have a certain set of skills to go through life with, in particular, let's say you want

00:17:04.480 --> 00:17:07.920
[Guest]: them to be college graduates, but you can't have eight kids.

00:17:07.920 --> 00:17:09.760
[Guest]: You can't have 13 kids.

00:17:09.760 --> 00:17:11.640
[Guest]: They're too expensive.

00:17:11.640 --> 00:17:16.960
[Guest]: So just financially and time-wise, not just money, time-wise also.

00:17:16.960 --> 00:17:24.920
[Guest]: So what he was trying to explain by that insight, which is trivial but deeply true to some extent,

00:17:24.920 --> 00:17:30.480
[Guest]: not the only factor, of course, but what he's trying to explain is that why do wealthy people

00:17:30.480 --> 00:17:35.160
[Guest]: have more nights out at restaurants?

00:17:35.160 --> 00:17:37.120
[Guest]: Why do they have more cars?

00:17:37.120 --> 00:17:39.600
[Guest]: Why do they have more square footage of house?

00:17:39.600 --> 00:17:40.600
[Guest]: Why don't they have more children?

00:17:40.600 --> 00:17:41.600
[Guest]: They like kids.

00:17:41.600 --> 00:17:42.600
[Guest]: Kids are things they like.

00:17:42.600 --> 00:17:43.600
[Guest]: They have lots of money.

00:17:43.600 --> 00:17:44.600
[Guest]: Why don't they have more of them?

00:17:44.600 --> 00:17:49.080
[Guest]: The answer is, which is interesting and provocative, is that, well, the more you have, the harder

00:17:49.080 --> 00:17:54.120
[Guest]: it is to have the level of investment you might want in knowledge and time to have them

00:17:54.120 --> 00:17:55.360
[Guest]: turn out a certain way.

00:17:55.360 --> 00:17:57.760
[Guest]: So that's really interesting.

00:17:57.760 --> 00:18:01.320
[Guest]: That's Becker's one insight that you get from using the economic tools.

00:18:01.320 --> 00:18:07.440
[Guest]: But you really wouldn't want to, I think, I don't think you want to assume that people

00:18:07.440 --> 00:18:13.640
[Guest]: sit around and think when they're getting married, honey, let's make sure we take care

00:18:13.640 --> 00:18:18.400
[Guest]: of the quantity quality trade off when we decide how many kids to have.

00:18:18.400 --> 00:18:21.560
[Guest]: Now Becker was a very wise man.

00:18:21.560 --> 00:18:28.080
[Guest]: He didn't think that's what people literally did, perhaps, that they were calculating machines.

00:18:28.080 --> 00:18:33.480
[Guest]: What he was trying to do is often called the as if hypothesis, saying, well, people act

00:18:33.480 --> 00:18:38.080
[Guest]: as if they're trying to maximize how much pleasure they get from their children.

00:18:38.080 --> 00:18:40.320
[Guest]: So I think that's a very powerful tool.

00:18:40.320 --> 00:18:44.400
[Guest]: But most economists don't realize, and this is where I want to get back to your question.

00:18:44.400 --> 00:18:50.480
[Guest]: It's a long, rambling answer, but most economists struggle to remember that their models of

00:18:50.480 --> 00:18:52.920
[Guest]: reality aren't the same as reality.

00:18:52.920 --> 00:18:55.140
[Guest]: I don't think, I'm not sure Gary Becker ever made that mistake.

00:18:55.140 --> 00:19:00.280
[Guest]: But most of us being human, more human, we make that mistake all the time.

00:19:00.280 --> 00:19:01.680
[Guest]: And you might argue, well, what's the difference?

00:19:01.680 --> 00:19:02.680
[Guest]: Not a big deal.

00:19:02.680 --> 00:19:06.240
[Guest]: But what the difference is, is that it starts to change how you look at human beings and

00:19:06.240 --> 00:19:07.240
[Guest]: how you look at yourself.

00:19:07.240 --> 00:19:10.280
[Guest]: And, you know, the example I like to use is the dance floor.

00:19:10.280 --> 00:19:15.160
[Guest]: When you go out on a dance floor with a partner, is your goal, the economist would say, oh,

00:19:15.160 --> 00:19:18.120
[Guest]: your goal is to get as much pleasure as you can from this experience.

00:19:18.120 --> 00:19:22.080
[Guest]: You might want to show off or have people think you're a great dancer.

00:19:22.080 --> 00:19:25.600
[Guest]: And what Adam Smith would actually say is that when you're out on a dance floor, there's

00:19:25.600 --> 00:19:31.240
[Guest]: certain rules of propriety, certain rules of conduct that you should live up to, certain

00:19:31.240 --> 00:19:32.240
[Guest]: expectations.

00:19:32.240 --> 00:19:35.200
[Guest]: So you're not trying to maximize anything.

00:19:35.200 --> 00:19:37.200
[Guest]: What you're trying to do is live by the rules.

00:19:37.200 --> 00:19:38.520
[Guest]: You're trying to be a good person.

00:19:38.520 --> 00:19:43.280
[Guest]: Now, those two worldviews, which are get the most out of every experience versus, well,

00:19:43.280 --> 00:19:46.200
[Guest]: in some settings, you know, I just try to do the right thing.

00:19:46.200 --> 00:19:48.120
[Guest]: Obviously, there's sometimes intention.

00:19:48.120 --> 00:19:53.120
[Guest]: A lot of times doing the right thing is expensive in some fashions, so we don't do the right

00:19:53.120 --> 00:19:54.120
[Guest]: things.

00:19:54.120 --> 00:19:57.480
[Guest]: I don't think you want to argue that the economic way of thinking is irrelevant.

00:19:57.480 --> 00:19:59.680
[Guest]: It's just that it's not the only thing.

00:19:59.680 --> 00:20:03.040
[Guest]: And so many times economists, I think, forget that.

00:20:03.040 --> 00:20:09.120
[Guest]: So to come back to your question about specialization, you know, most economists know very little

00:20:09.120 --> 00:20:13.160
[Guest]: about other things outside of mathematical theory and statistics.

00:20:13.160 --> 00:20:16.840
[Guest]: You might think, oh, it's because they're so – they don't have time, and it's not

00:20:16.840 --> 00:20:17.840
[Guest]: the reason.

00:20:17.840 --> 00:20:18.840
[Guest]: The reason is they're not interested.

00:20:18.840 --> 00:20:20.440
[Guest]: They're not so interested in art history.

00:20:20.440 --> 00:20:22.840
[Guest]: They're not so interested in poetry.

00:20:22.840 --> 00:20:26.920
[Guest]: It's just not – that's the kind of person who's interested in math and statistics often

00:20:26.920 --> 00:20:33.440
[Guest]: sometimes, isn't interested in a wider range of things.

00:20:33.440 --> 00:20:39.720
[Guest]: So I think the biggest challenge that academics face today in the world isn't just that they're

00:20:39.720 --> 00:20:41.560
[Guest]: not interdisciplinary.

00:20:41.560 --> 00:20:45.360
[Guest]: That's one way to phrase your – the point you raised.

00:20:45.360 --> 00:20:50.800
[Guest]: They don't understand things outside their narrow silo of how they were trained.

00:20:50.800 --> 00:20:56.680
[Guest]: I think it's more – there's a meta-understanding there that's missing, which is we don't

00:20:56.680 --> 00:21:03.480
[Guest]: understand often as academics how much our worldview is conditioned on the way we were

00:21:03.480 --> 00:21:04.480
[Guest]: trained.

00:21:04.480 --> 00:21:06.680
[Guest]: Let me give you an example.

00:21:06.680 --> 00:21:12.440
[Guest]: You're raised in a household that has a respect for religion, and you end up adopting – most

00:21:12.440 --> 00:21:16.120
[Guest]: people do – their parents' religion, or they leave their parents' religion, which

00:21:16.120 --> 00:21:17.800
[Guest]: is the other thing that happens.

00:21:17.800 --> 00:21:20.200
[Guest]: But let's say you keep your parents' religion.

00:21:20.200 --> 00:21:25.880
[Guest]: The idea that you spend much or any time thinking about whether it's the right religion is

00:21:25.880 --> 00:21:28.200
[Guest]: almost zero.

00:21:28.200 --> 00:21:29.480
[Guest]: It's like it's discomforting.

00:21:29.480 --> 00:21:32.240
[Guest]: You don't want to think about it, and you're happy.

00:21:32.240 --> 00:21:34.080
[Guest]: You got a good thing going.

00:21:34.080 --> 00:21:35.200
[Guest]: That's the way you were raised.

00:21:35.200 --> 00:21:40.720
[Guest]: There's deep primal things that are going on there with family and the transition from

00:21:40.720 --> 00:21:45.760
[Guest]: childhood to adulthood, the existential angst of being a human being that you don't want

00:21:45.760 --> 00:21:47.000
[Guest]: to tamper with.

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:49.400
[Guest]: So academics have that same problem.

00:21:49.400 --> 00:21:50.720
[Guest]: They don't even realize it.

00:21:50.720 --> 00:21:54.280
[Guest]: We're trained in a certain – I can't – I don't want to repeat the actual people,

00:21:54.280 --> 00:21:59.720
[Guest]: but friends of mine, colleagues of mine, and fellow economists will write me and say – or

00:21:59.720 --> 00:22:04.800
[Guest]: talk to me and say, you sound like you're kind of skeptical about fill-in-the-blank.

00:22:04.800 --> 00:22:07.400
[Guest]: I'm thinking, well, sure, aren't you?

00:22:07.400 --> 00:22:08.960
[Guest]: I realize, no, they're not.

00:22:08.960 --> 00:22:09.960
[Guest]: They haven't thought about it.

00:22:09.960 --> 00:22:10.960
[Guest]: I don't know.

00:22:10.960 --> 00:22:12.640
[Guest]: This isn't like, oh, I'm so much better than them.

00:22:12.640 --> 00:22:13.640
[Guest]: They don't think about it.

00:22:13.640 --> 00:22:19.000
[Guest]: I'm talking about the fact that when you're a fish in water, you just don't realize you're

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:20.000
[Guest]: in the water.

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:23.400
[Guest]: I mean that's just such an obvious challenge of being a fish.

00:22:23.400 --> 00:22:25.760
[Guest]: If you're a fish, you don't need to think about it.

00:22:25.760 --> 00:22:26.760
[Guest]: It's not important.

00:22:26.760 --> 00:22:27.760
[Guest]: You're in the water.

00:22:27.760 --> 00:22:28.760
[Guest]: You can't live on land.

00:22:28.760 --> 00:22:33.160
[Guest]: It's not like you're missing a big opportunity that all you're thinking about is the water.

00:22:33.160 --> 00:22:38.760
[Guest]: But if you're an academic and all you can see are the studies that confirm your way

00:22:38.760 --> 00:22:43.600
[Guest]: of looking at the world, you're in water and it's costing you because you don't

00:22:43.600 --> 00:22:46.560
[Guest]: realize that the world is more complicated.

00:22:46.560 --> 00:22:55.280
[Guest]: So even super intelligent, high IQ, prestigious, successful academics that I talk to, they

00:22:55.280 --> 00:22:59.040
[Guest]: don't spend any time questioning the tools they've been trained in.

00:22:59.040 --> 00:23:04.120
[Guest]: I mean it's like saying, I wonder what it would be like to live in a thatched hut.

00:23:04.120 --> 00:23:08.440
[Guest]: Most people who live in suburban America don't think about thatched huts that much.

00:23:08.440 --> 00:23:14.560
[Guest]: I wonder what it's like to live in a yurt or what it would be like to ride a bicycle

00:23:14.560 --> 00:23:15.560
[Guest]: to work every day.

00:23:15.560 --> 00:23:16.560
[Guest]: That's a stretch.

00:23:16.560 --> 00:23:18.960
[Guest]: Some people do that and they realize, oh, it's kind of fun.

00:23:18.960 --> 00:23:26.080
[Guest]: But within your academic discipline to turn on it or to imagine that there's a richer

00:23:26.080 --> 00:23:30.240
[Guest]: or more complicated view of the world or that you're leaving out stuff, that's another

00:23:30.240 --> 00:23:32.440
[Guest]: way to think about it.

00:23:32.440 --> 00:23:38.560
[Guest]: One thing I've been increasingly interested in is this challenge of thinking about data

00:23:38.560 --> 00:23:43.360
[Guest]: and measurability and so much of life is not measurable.

00:23:43.360 --> 00:23:46.440
[Guest]: Just don't even think about those things that aren't measured.

00:23:46.440 --> 00:23:49.200
[Guest]: It's not like, oh, well, we can't measure that, but we'll keep it in mind.

00:23:49.200 --> 00:23:50.200
[Guest]: It's out of mind.

00:23:50.200 --> 00:23:52.480
[Guest]: It's out of sight.

00:23:52.480 --> 00:23:55.320
[Guest]: My line is dignity is not in the data set.

00:23:55.320 --> 00:23:59.880
[Guest]: There's no variable called dignity that goes on a scale of zero to 10.

00:23:59.880 --> 00:24:05.000
[Guest]: It's like if I go to an out-of-work coal miner in West Virginia and say, on a scale

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:09.760
[Guest]: of zero to 10, how much self-worth are you feeling today?

00:24:09.760 --> 00:24:10.760
[Guest]: We don't ask those questions.

00:24:10.760 --> 00:24:11.760
[Guest]: Nobody asks those questions.

00:24:11.760 --> 00:24:16.200
[Guest]: If you do, the answers don't mean anything, and they vary from day to day.

00:24:16.200 --> 00:24:17.680
[Guest]: But that's important.

00:24:17.680 --> 00:24:19.440
[Guest]: Dignity is important.

00:24:19.440 --> 00:24:20.440
[Guest]: Work is important.

00:24:20.440 --> 00:24:21.720
[Guest]: It's not just how much we earn.

00:24:21.720 --> 00:24:28.560
[Guest]: It's the work we do and how satisfied we are by it and how proud we are of it.

00:24:28.560 --> 00:24:31.120
[Guest]: Economists just ignore all this stuff because it can't be measured.

00:24:31.120 --> 00:24:35.120
[Guest]: We say in the back of our mind, well, of course, we know about that, but after a while, we

00:24:35.120 --> 00:24:36.840
[Guest]: forget about it.

00:24:36.840 --> 00:24:38.320
[Guest]: That leads to policy mistakes.

00:24:38.320 --> 00:24:39.320
[Guest]: It leads to hubris.

00:24:39.320 --> 00:24:41.360
[Guest]: That's a really long answer.

00:24:41.360 --> 00:24:42.360
[Guest]: I apologize.

00:24:42.360 --> 00:24:49.680
[Guest]: But this question of narrowness, I think, is much more than just that we're not interdisciplinary,

00:24:49.680 --> 00:24:51.800
[Guest]: which most of us aren't.

00:24:51.800 --> 00:24:57.160
[Guest]: In fact, George Stigler, another one of my professors at Chicago, said there's only one

00:24:57.160 --> 00:25:04.120
[Guest]: social science and we are its practitioners, meaning economists.

00:25:04.120 --> 00:25:05.800
[Guest]: That's the way a lot of economists feel.

00:25:05.800 --> 00:25:10.080
[Guest]: It's like our tools, that's the only way to look at the family.

00:25:10.080 --> 00:25:11.080
[Guest]: Sociologists don't have anything.

00:25:11.080 --> 00:25:12.560
[Guest]: They just make up stuff.

00:25:12.560 --> 00:25:17.600
[Guest]: That's sort of the – just as another biographical note, Gary Becker was interested in sociology

00:25:17.600 --> 00:25:19.400
[Guest]: and he realized there's nothing here.

00:25:19.400 --> 00:25:24.920
[Guest]: Now, there's some brilliant sociologists, but the field of sociology doesn't have

00:25:24.920 --> 00:25:27.160
[Guest]: an organized theories.

00:25:27.160 --> 00:25:31.520
[Guest]: So I think economics was deeply appealing to him because it gave him a framework for

00:25:31.520 --> 00:25:36.120
[Guest]: organizing his thinking about the family, about what we would normally call sociology

00:25:36.120 --> 00:25:37.120
[Guest]: or anthropology.

00:25:37.120 --> 00:25:40.760
[Guest]: It's a powerful tool, but it's not the whole story.

00:25:40.760 --> 00:25:41.760
[Guest]: I think Gary knew that.

00:25:41.760 --> 00:25:43.800
[Amit Varma]: I think a lot of economists struggle to remember it.

00:25:43.800 --> 00:25:48.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and I'm very interested in sort of the question of how we form our belief systems.

00:25:48.600 --> 00:25:52.680
[Amit Varma]: Like when we are young, we're trying to make sense of the world and suddenly you come across

00:25:52.680 --> 00:25:56.160
[Amit Varma]: a framework that explains everything and it feels so powerful.

00:25:56.160 --> 00:25:59.280
[Amit Varma]: It's almost like your eyes pop out of your head because you see everything clearly for

00:25:59.280 --> 00:26:04.240
[Amit Varma]: the first time and then that's like a hammer you apply to every single nail and you've

00:26:04.240 --> 00:26:08.800
[Amit Varma]: made the analogy for a bunch of people have lost a key and they're all gathered around

00:26:08.800 --> 00:26:12.040
[Amit Varma]: the lamppost looking for the key, even though the key is somewhere else, but they are where

00:26:12.040 --> 00:26:13.040
[Amit Varma]: the light is.

00:26:13.040 --> 00:26:14.040
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, exactly.

00:26:14.040 --> 00:26:16.640
[Amit Varma]: You know, and that strikes me as being very accurate.

00:26:16.640 --> 00:26:22.200
[Amit Varma]: I was sort of saving my question on ideology for later about how one deals with ideologies

00:26:22.200 --> 00:26:23.680
[Amit Varma]: and things about ideologies.

00:26:23.680 --> 00:26:29.400
[Amit Varma]: But since you've sort of brought that subject up in your book on Adam Smith's, you quoted

00:26:29.400 --> 00:26:33.560
[Amit Varma]: Sam Thompson as saying, quote, the universe is full of dots, connect the right ones and

00:26:33.560 --> 00:26:34.880
[Amit Varma]: you can draw anything.

00:26:34.880 --> 00:26:38.520
[Amit Varma]: The important question is not whether the dots you picked are really there, but why

00:26:38.520 --> 00:26:40.800
[Amit Varma]: you chose to ignore all the others.

00:26:40.800 --> 00:26:41.800
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:26:41.800 --> 00:26:45.000
[Amit Varma]: And you've also, you know, you've had Arnold King on your show and he wrote this great

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:47.440
[Amit Varma]: book called The Three Languages of Politics.

00:26:47.440 --> 00:26:52.280
[Amit Varma]: Before I ask you to elaborate, I'll quickly sort of summarize that for my listeners.

00:26:52.280 --> 00:26:57.760
[Amit Varma]: Arnold's argument essentially is that if you look at the three major ideologies in America

00:26:57.760 --> 00:27:00.760
[Amit Varma]: today, it's not a question of somebody being right or wrong.

00:27:00.760 --> 00:27:04.000
[Amit Varma]: It's just that they are starting from different first principles.

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:06.560
[Amit Varma]: And from that point on, they are completely coherent.

00:27:06.560 --> 00:27:12.440
[Amit Varma]: And I'll, you know, quote from your piece in this, where you write, quote, liberals

00:27:12.440 --> 00:27:16.880
[Amit Varma]: see the world as a battle between victims and oppressors, conservatives see the world

00:27:16.880 --> 00:27:21.760
[Amit Varma]: as a battle between civilization and barbarism, libertarians see the world as a battle between

00:27:21.760 --> 00:27:22.760
[Amit Varma]: freedom and coercion.

00:27:22.760 --> 00:27:23.760
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:27:23.760 --> 00:27:27.920
[Amit Varma]: And by liberals, of course, you mean the American style liberals, I guess we could also call

00:27:27.920 --> 00:27:28.920
[Amit Varma]: them progressives.

00:27:28.920 --> 00:27:33.360
[Amit Varma]: Otherwise, you know, you and I would call ourselves liberals, I think broadly.

00:27:33.360 --> 00:27:37.560
[Amit Varma]: And you wrote a very interesting piece where you sort of pointed out that, well, of course,

00:27:37.560 --> 00:27:41.960
[Amit Varma]: this is true, that we are often talking past each other and not to each other, because

00:27:41.960 --> 00:27:45.760
[Amit Varma]: we don't recognize each other's priors and try to understand where the person is coming

00:27:45.760 --> 00:27:46.760
[Amit Varma]: from.

00:27:46.760 --> 00:27:52.240
[Amit Varma]: But you also pointed out that these three tribes, as it were, also have their own sort

00:27:52.240 --> 00:27:58.840
[Amit Varma]: of blind spots, which stop them from, you know, seeing the world, which I found incredibly

00:27:58.840 --> 00:28:03.960
[Amit Varma]: fascinating, because when I read it, my first instinct was, yeah, he's right about the liberals

00:28:03.960 --> 00:28:04.960
[Amit Varma]: or the progressives.

00:28:04.960 --> 00:28:06.680
[Amit Varma]: And yeah, he's right about the conservatives.

00:28:06.680 --> 00:28:12.160
[Amit Varma]: Well, how is he right about the libertarians, but, you know, then one kind of reads it carefully

00:28:12.160 --> 00:28:14.440
[Amit Varma]: and sees the points that you're making.

00:28:14.440 --> 00:28:15.800
[Amit Varma]: Can you elaborate on that a bit?

00:28:15.800 --> 00:28:16.800
[Amit Varma]: What are these blind spots?

00:28:16.800 --> 00:28:21.800
[Amit Varma]: And also, you know, before you get to that, is that something that you have changed your

00:28:21.800 --> 00:28:23.160
[Amit Varma]: mind over time?

00:28:23.160 --> 00:28:27.360
[Amit Varma]: Like were you once sort of more dogmatic than you are today?

00:28:27.360 --> 00:28:32.000
[Guest]: Yeah, that's a good question and hard to, I'm going to get lost answering it, but maybe

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:33.600
[Guest]: you could steer me back if I get in trouble.

00:28:33.600 --> 00:28:36.240
[Guest]: So let's start with the three languages.

00:28:36.240 --> 00:28:39.680
[Guest]: That comes from Arnold Kling, as you point out in his book, The Three Languages of Politics,

00:28:39.680 --> 00:28:44.840
[Guest]: a fantastic short read that will change the way you look at politics, one of the most

00:28:44.840 --> 00:28:47.560
[Guest]: influential books on my thinking.

00:28:47.560 --> 00:28:52.440
[Guest]: You know, those three lenses, those three frameworks, so I'm going to call them progressive

00:28:52.440 --> 00:28:54.240
[Guest]: to keep that confusion from happening.

00:28:54.240 --> 00:28:59.560
[Guest]: So progressives say the world is full of victims and oppressors.

00:28:59.560 --> 00:29:05.280
[Guest]: Conservatives say the world is a fight between barbarism and civilization, and libertarians

00:29:05.280 --> 00:29:08.080
[Guest]: say the world's a fight between freedom and coercion.

00:29:08.080 --> 00:29:14.920
[Guest]: So let's take an example in the current situation in America, police brutality.

00:29:14.920 --> 00:29:19.840
[Guest]: The death of George Floyd recently, the tragic death of George Floyd, the progressives look

00:29:19.840 --> 00:29:26.200
[Guest]: at that and say black people are victims and the police are oppressors.

00:29:26.200 --> 00:29:31.280
[Guest]: The conservatives look at it and say being a policeman is a very hard job.

00:29:31.280 --> 00:29:33.260
[Guest]: Police officer is a very hard job.

00:29:33.260 --> 00:29:36.720
[Guest]: If we don't honor them, we're going to have a breakdown in order.

00:29:36.720 --> 00:29:40.680
[Guest]: We're going to have looting and rioting and look, look what's happening.

00:29:40.680 --> 00:29:44.200
[Guest]: The libertarians say the police are doing all the wrong stuff.

00:29:44.200 --> 00:29:49.680
[Guest]: They're obsessed with the drug war, which causes them to really run amok.

00:29:49.680 --> 00:29:52.800
[Guest]: Policing should be a personal choice of an individual, shouldn't be the government's

00:29:52.800 --> 00:29:53.800
[Guest]: role.

00:29:53.800 --> 00:29:57.080
[Guest]: Police should stay out of that and most of these problems would go away.

00:29:57.080 --> 00:30:02.040
[Guest]: Now the irony is I think all three of those things are true.

00:30:02.040 --> 00:30:03.960
[Guest]: I think all three of those things are true.

00:30:03.960 --> 00:30:08.040
[Guest]: I think black people are oppressed in America.

00:30:08.040 --> 00:30:12.440
[Guest]: I think civilization is a threat from barbarism, and I think the government ought to get out

00:30:12.440 --> 00:30:14.000
[Guest]: of the drug war.

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:15.000
[Guest]: That's not what's interesting.

00:30:15.000 --> 00:30:22.360
[Guest]: What's interesting is that it's very hard for each of us to see beyond our own lens.

00:30:22.360 --> 00:30:29.680
[Guest]: And so all I can see when I put my glasses on, if I'm a conservative is, oh my gosh,

00:30:29.680 --> 00:30:31.440
[Guest]: this looting is out of control.

00:30:31.440 --> 00:30:33.480
[Guest]: My house could get attacked.

00:30:33.480 --> 00:30:34.800
[Guest]: I could get attacked.

00:30:34.800 --> 00:30:37.040
[Guest]: We need strong police.

00:30:37.040 --> 00:30:42.560
[Guest]: The progressives look at it and saying, do you know what it's like to be black in America?

00:30:42.560 --> 00:30:45.840
[Guest]: Police look at it and saying, yeah, those police have all this military equipment.

00:30:45.840 --> 00:30:50.840
[Guest]: So every person is seeing it through their own lens and they're not wrong.

00:30:50.840 --> 00:30:54.600
[Guest]: What changed for me from Arnold's book and other conversations and thinking about is

00:30:54.600 --> 00:30:59.120
[Guest]: that you got to realize the other side's got some good points.

00:30:59.120 --> 00:31:00.120
[Guest]: They're not wrong.

00:31:00.120 --> 00:31:01.640
[Guest]: They're not right.

00:31:01.640 --> 00:31:05.120
[Guest]: Not the whole story, but they're not wrong.

00:31:05.120 --> 00:31:08.280
[Guest]: So all three of those I think are correct.

00:31:08.280 --> 00:31:09.540
[Guest]: And now what do you do?

00:31:09.540 --> 00:31:13.400
[Guest]: And my point in that essay that you're referring to is that I think each of those views, while

00:31:13.400 --> 00:31:15.280
[Guest]: correct, has a blind spot.

00:31:15.280 --> 00:31:19.080
[Guest]: So in the case of progressives, they think the victims have no agency.

00:31:19.080 --> 00:31:20.080
[Guest]: They can't help.

00:31:20.080 --> 00:31:22.480
[Guest]: They have no options, no freedom.

00:31:22.480 --> 00:31:23.480
[Guest]: That's absurd.

00:31:23.480 --> 00:31:26.080
[Guest]: That's a ridiculous thing to believe, right?

00:31:26.080 --> 00:31:31.240
[Guest]: So that lens of, of course, blacks are oppressed at times and have a tough time.

00:31:31.240 --> 00:31:32.240
[Guest]: That's true.

00:31:32.240 --> 00:31:36.040
[Guest]: But to then go so far as to say they have no agency, there's nothing they can do about

00:31:36.040 --> 00:31:37.800
[Guest]: their situation.

00:31:37.800 --> 00:31:41.240
[Guest]: It's impossible to make any progress as a black person in America.

00:31:41.240 --> 00:31:42.480
[Guest]: That's absurd.

00:31:42.480 --> 00:31:48.180
[Guest]: That's not, that's not consistent with the data, the facts, the reality that we all understand.

00:31:48.180 --> 00:31:53.320
[Guest]: And similarly, the conservative is right that we want to make sure that the people can go

00:31:53.320 --> 00:31:59.400
[Guest]: safely about their business and, and, and walk down the street and have good businesses.

00:31:59.400 --> 00:32:01.720
[Guest]: But they often don't think that everything's the fault.

00:32:01.720 --> 00:32:04.200
[Guest]: The police never make a mistake, but of course they do.

00:32:04.200 --> 00:32:05.880
[Guest]: They do some terrible things.

00:32:05.880 --> 00:32:09.880
[Guest]: They're human beings and it's, they're a small portion, perhaps, doesn't matter.

00:32:09.880 --> 00:32:12.880
[Guest]: It should be smaller if we can do it ideally.

00:32:12.880 --> 00:32:16.840
[Guest]: So the conservatives, you know, I have a lot of conservative friends and I'm increasingly

00:32:16.840 --> 00:32:19.000
[Guest]: interested in conservative ideas.

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:23.160
[Guest]: You know, they'll say things like, well, there's all this employment opportunity.

00:32:23.160 --> 00:32:26.960
[Guest]: Not right now, of course, because the pandemic, but before the pandemic, they'd say, why are

00:32:26.960 --> 00:32:30.440
[Guest]: all these people in, in inner cities in America, why are they doing drugs?

00:32:30.440 --> 00:32:31.680
[Guest]: Why aren't they working?

00:32:31.680 --> 00:32:32.680
[Guest]: That's their fault.

00:32:32.680 --> 00:32:33.680
[Guest]: Why aren't they getting a job?

00:32:33.680 --> 00:32:37.280
[Guest]: There's, look at all the employees, if I were black, I wouldn't be like that.

00:32:37.280 --> 00:32:38.880
[Guest]: I'm thinking, how could you say that?

00:32:38.880 --> 00:32:41.600
[Guest]: You have no idea what it's like to be black.

00:32:41.600 --> 00:32:42.600
[Guest]: You're not black.

00:32:42.600 --> 00:32:45.680
[Guest]: And you really think you'd be different?

00:32:45.680 --> 00:32:49.800
[Guest]: You wouldn't be like them if you didn't have a decent education, if you grew up in a bunch

00:32:49.800 --> 00:32:54.040
[Guest]: of streets where everything was boarded up, you really think you'd be this?

00:32:54.040 --> 00:32:57.880
[Guest]: So, so the progressives think that poor people have no agency.

00:32:57.880 --> 00:33:02.680
[Guest]: They're just victims of rich exploiting companies and, and a racism.

00:33:02.680 --> 00:33:04.040
[Guest]: The conservative makes the opposite mistake.

00:33:04.040 --> 00:33:05.240
[Guest]: Oh, you can do anything you want.

00:33:05.240 --> 00:33:06.240
[Guest]: It's a free country.

00:33:06.240 --> 00:33:07.840
[Guest]: Why aren't you making something of yourself?

00:33:07.840 --> 00:33:13.600
[Guest]: The answer is because you've got too many handicaps, racism, bad education, a tough

00:33:13.600 --> 00:33:16.120
[Guest]: home situation, a horrible neighborhood.

00:33:16.120 --> 00:33:19.360
[Guest]: So the each side is having to learn from each other.

00:33:19.360 --> 00:33:26.120
[Guest]: But the I think the deeper point is that our discourse, which in America and elsewhere

00:33:26.120 --> 00:33:29.280
[Guest]: now is increasingly tribal.

00:33:29.280 --> 00:33:34.880
[Guest]: It's increasingly, I'm not just right and you're wrong.

00:33:34.880 --> 00:33:38.040
[Guest]: It's I'm right and you're a threat.

00:33:38.040 --> 00:33:39.920
[Guest]: You're a threat to civilization.

00:33:39.920 --> 00:33:45.640
[Guest]: You're a threat to poor people, black people.

00:33:45.640 --> 00:33:48.720
[Guest]: Each side sees the other as an existential threat.

00:33:48.720 --> 00:33:50.560
[Guest]: And I, you know, I learned this from Sebastian Junger.

00:33:50.560 --> 00:33:52.480
[Guest]: He wrote a beautiful book called Tribe.

00:33:52.480 --> 00:33:59.240
[Guest]: So, you know, if you think that the other side is destroying the country, which is what

00:33:59.240 --> 00:34:04.600
[Guest]: is the case in America right now, the progressives think the conservatives are literally destroying

00:34:04.600 --> 00:34:09.280
[Guest]: the country and the conservatives literally think that the progressives are destroying

00:34:09.280 --> 00:34:10.640
[Guest]: the country.

00:34:10.640 --> 00:34:14.000
[Guest]: You're accusing your opponents of treason.

00:34:14.000 --> 00:34:18.160
[Guest]: And treason is usually punishable by the death penalty in human history.

00:34:18.160 --> 00:34:20.840
[Guest]: And you start to think about what these kind of attitudes are going to justify.

00:34:20.840 --> 00:34:22.040
[Guest]: And we see it right now.

00:34:22.040 --> 00:34:29.240
[Guest]: We see in America the media is spiraling out of control because they feel that the quote

00:34:29.240 --> 00:34:35.960
[Guest]: other side, doesn't matter which side we're talking about, the other side is an existential

00:34:35.960 --> 00:34:39.240
[Guest]: threat to the future of the country.

00:34:39.240 --> 00:34:40.240
[Guest]: It can't last.

00:34:40.240 --> 00:34:43.240
[Guest]: It's got to either get fixed or it's going to end up in violence.

00:34:43.240 --> 00:34:44.960
[Guest]: It's a scary, scary time.

00:34:44.960 --> 00:34:50.320
[Guest]: So to come back to your original question or observation, the quote from Sam Thompson,

00:34:50.320 --> 00:34:56.120
[Guest]: one of my listeners or readers, I don't remember whether I got heard from him in an email,

00:34:56.120 --> 00:34:59.880
[Guest]: that beautiful quote about cherry picking facts.

00:34:59.880 --> 00:35:01.160
[Guest]: There's so many facts.

00:35:01.160 --> 00:35:05.280
[Guest]: It's very easy to convince yourself that the facts support your view.

00:35:05.280 --> 00:35:06.680
[Guest]: Can't tell many people I debate with it.

00:35:06.680 --> 00:35:12.960
[Guest]: They actually believe that a handful of facts means they've proved their case, forgetting

00:35:12.960 --> 00:35:17.960
[Guest]: that sometimes the facts are literally not facts, that there are other facts that contradict

00:35:17.960 --> 00:35:21.160
[Guest]: their case and they don't even imagine it.

00:35:21.160 --> 00:35:25.280
[Guest]: I mean, it's not like, oh, I have a pretty good case and maybe, maybe I need to rethink

00:35:25.280 --> 00:35:26.280
[Guest]: some things.

00:35:26.280 --> 00:35:28.680
[Guest]: It's like, this is open and shut.

00:35:28.680 --> 00:35:35.240
[Guest]: And so the idea of being open to things, not being open and shut, I think is really important.

00:35:35.240 --> 00:35:37.600
[Guest]: It's not that good for your podcast audience.

00:35:37.600 --> 00:35:44.720
[Guest]: I think the angrier you are and the more confident you are, you then gather around you, your

00:35:44.720 --> 00:35:49.480
[Guest]: choir of voices that will reinforce your attitudes.

00:35:49.480 --> 00:35:52.560
[Guest]: And I just don't want to be part of that.

00:35:52.560 --> 00:35:53.560
[Guest]: I think that's a mistake.

00:35:53.560 --> 00:35:54.760
[Guest]: I think that's wrong.

00:35:54.760 --> 00:35:57.800
[Guest]: And I think that's part of the problem.

00:35:57.800 --> 00:36:03.600
[Guest]: Everybody's in their own silo right now of, of, of reinforcing their own views.

00:36:03.600 --> 00:36:05.240
[Guest]: And the internet's really good at that.

00:36:05.240 --> 00:36:06.720
[Amit Varma]: No, I'm just thinking aloud.

00:36:06.720 --> 00:36:12.880
[Amit Varma]: It strikes me that what we are probably seeing today is an intersection of a particular way

00:36:12.880 --> 00:36:17.720
[Amit Varma]: in which we are hardwired coming together with the way technology has evolved.

00:36:17.720 --> 00:36:22.840
[Amit Varma]: And I'm sort of going to, you know, forgive me if I ramble, but I'm going to quote from

00:36:22.840 --> 00:36:26.920
[Amit Varma]: Adam Smith, a theory of moral sentiments, as I try to sort of elaborate on this, where

00:36:26.920 --> 00:36:31.380
[Amit Varma]: Smith says, quote, the chief part of human happiness arises from the consciousness of

00:36:31.380 --> 00:36:32.380
[Amit Varma]: being beloved.

00:36:32.380 --> 00:36:36.560
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote, which is, in a sense, you know, almost banal, obviously, we are all seeking

00:36:36.560 --> 00:36:39.160
[Amit Varma]: validation, we are hardwired to seek validation.

00:36:39.160 --> 00:36:43.560
[Amit Varma]: And what's happened in modern times is that earlier, you know, that when the theory of

00:36:43.560 --> 00:36:47.800
[Amit Varma]: moral sentiments was written, obviously, it was written with a small group of people in

00:36:47.800 --> 00:36:51.760
[Amit Varma]: mind, which is your family and your friends and the people you know, personally.

00:36:51.760 --> 00:36:56.520
[Amit Varma]: And we also evolved at a time where we knew very few people, we didn't have access to

00:36:56.520 --> 00:36:58.040
[Amit Varma]: millions and billions of people.

00:36:58.040 --> 00:37:00.480
[Amit Varma]: So our instincts evolve accordingly.

00:37:00.480 --> 00:37:05.520
[Amit Varma]: So when we seek validation from a small group, you know, there is the sort of the benefit

00:37:05.520 --> 00:37:09.480
[Amit Varma]: of posturing is a little less because they will be with us long enough to see through

00:37:09.480 --> 00:37:14.280
[Amit Varma]: that and we aren't being able to posture at scale to so many people.

00:37:14.280 --> 00:37:20.560
[Amit Varma]: And what technology has done is that it becomes really easy to go online to find an echo chamber

00:37:20.560 --> 00:37:25.160
[Amit Varma]: of people who happen to believe whatever frame you view the world through or whatever worldview

00:37:25.160 --> 00:37:26.160
[Amit Varma]: you have.

00:37:26.160 --> 00:37:31.280
[Amit Varma]: And then the incentives are aligned, not towards having conversations with people who might,

00:37:31.280 --> 00:37:35.520
[Amit Varma]: you know, behave differently with you, but towards raising your status within this little

00:37:35.520 --> 00:37:36.520
[Amit Varma]: in group.

00:37:36.520 --> 00:37:40.640
[Amit Varma]: And increasingly, the way to do that is to get more and more shrill, whether you're attacking

00:37:40.640 --> 00:37:44.800
[Amit Varma]: the other side, or whether you're signaling your own virtue, or whether you're attacking

00:37:44.800 --> 00:37:49.680
[Amit Varma]: people on your own side for not passing, you know, a specific purity test.

00:37:49.680 --> 00:37:55.200
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, you know, Cass Sunstein use the phrase group polarization for what basically

00:37:55.200 --> 00:37:56.200
[Amit Varma]: happens.

00:37:56.200 --> 00:37:59.800
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting that you kind of started your podcast and your great blog cafe hype

00:37:59.800 --> 00:38:03.600
[Amit Varma]: when you co wrote that with Don Woodrow, you know, back in the day before things became

00:38:03.600 --> 00:38:08.520
[Amit Varma]: so bad, like, I think this is really happened, maybe post Twitter really taking off post

00:38:08.520 --> 00:38:12.680
[Amit Varma]: 2010, that things have gotten so polarized and ugly.

00:38:12.680 --> 00:38:17.880
[Amit Varma]: So you know, what was that journey for you like of, you know, first seeing all of this

00:38:17.880 --> 00:38:20.520
[Amit Varma]: evolve, making sense of it.

00:38:20.520 --> 00:38:23.120
[Amit Varma]: And then in a sense, you are part of the circus, right?

00:38:23.120 --> 00:38:24.120
[Amit Varma]: You are on Twitter?

00:38:24.120 --> 00:38:25.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:38:25.120 --> 00:38:26.120
[Amit Varma]: What are your thoughts on all of this?

00:38:26.120 --> 00:38:27.120
[Guest]: Does it make you despair?

00:38:27.120 --> 00:38:32.800
[Guest]: Yeah, I want to add one thing to your very nice summary of where we are right now.

00:38:32.800 --> 00:38:39.960
[Guest]: I think the especially relevant comment given the title of your program, The Seen and the

00:38:39.960 --> 00:38:41.040
[Guest]: Unseen.

00:38:41.040 --> 00:38:51.040
[Guest]: So what we see is the Twitter mob, cancel culture, the descending anger of people on

00:38:51.040 --> 00:38:59.360
[Guest]: a particular individual who has violated some norm of civility or not civility, a norm of

00:38:59.360 --> 00:39:01.200
[Guest]: the right way of thinking.

00:39:01.200 --> 00:39:03.040
[Guest]: So that's what we see.

00:39:03.040 --> 00:39:05.160
[Guest]: And we're having a conversation about that right now in America.

00:39:05.160 --> 00:39:13.320
[Guest]: There was a recent letter signed out of Harper's Magazine about criticizing cancel culture.

00:39:13.320 --> 00:39:18.780
[Guest]: Fascinating sociological moment in America, because the people who signed that letter

00:39:18.780 --> 00:39:22.920
[Guest]: were very diverse politically.

00:39:22.920 --> 00:39:28.200
[Guest]: And that meant that there were some people who signed the letter who you're not supposed

00:39:28.200 --> 00:39:29.440
[Guest]: to like.

00:39:29.440 --> 00:39:33.160
[Guest]: And some people rescinded their signature because they said, oh, I didn't realize so-and-so

00:39:33.160 --> 00:39:34.160
[Guest]: signed it.

00:39:34.160 --> 00:39:37.960
[Guest]: I saw that this person signed it, and I think she's OK.

00:39:37.960 --> 00:39:42.840
[Guest]: But when I realized, oh, my gosh, so-and-so signed it, I'm sorry, I'm off, I'm out.

00:39:42.840 --> 00:39:44.520
[Guest]: So that's on the table right now.

00:39:44.520 --> 00:39:46.720
[Guest]: That's what's being talked about.

00:39:46.720 --> 00:39:47.720
[Guest]: That's what's seen.

00:39:47.720 --> 00:39:50.920
[Guest]: But I think the unseen is what's more interesting right now.

00:39:50.920 --> 00:39:58.760
[Guest]: And it's always more valuable to point out or more fun to point out what's not obvious.

00:39:58.760 --> 00:40:01.800
[Guest]: We just had a conversation about the three languages of politics.

00:40:01.800 --> 00:40:04.560
[Guest]: I chose to talk about police brutality as an example.

00:40:04.560 --> 00:40:10.000
[Guest]: You can take what's amazing about Kling's insights or you can apply it to almost every

00:40:10.000 --> 00:40:11.000
[Guest]: issue.

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:12.860
[Guest]: It breaks down that way.

00:40:12.860 --> 00:40:17.280
[Guest]: I was a little bit uneasy, mentioned in George Floyd on this program.

00:40:17.280 --> 00:40:20.960
[Guest]: It's like in the back of my mind, it's a sort of nagging fear.

00:40:20.960 --> 00:40:27.160
[Guest]: What if I make a misstep and I say something that's politically incorrect and somebody

00:40:27.160 --> 00:40:32.080
[Guest]: takes it out of context and puts it on Twitter and accuses me of being a racist?

00:40:32.080 --> 00:40:33.600
[Guest]: Like that's no fun.

00:40:33.600 --> 00:40:34.600
[Guest]: I took a chance.

00:40:34.600 --> 00:40:35.600
[Guest]: I talked about it.

00:40:35.600 --> 00:40:36.600
[Guest]: That's so dangerous.

00:40:36.600 --> 00:40:45.840
[Guest]: But I think the unseen that's important in this cancel culture moment is the thoughts

00:40:45.840 --> 00:40:51.640
[Guest]: that we have and the words that we say, that we either push back down those thoughts because

00:40:51.640 --> 00:40:53.040
[Guest]: oh, that's trouble.

00:40:53.040 --> 00:40:55.040
[Guest]: I'm staying away from that.

00:40:55.040 --> 00:40:56.040
[Guest]: Or quiet.

00:40:56.040 --> 00:41:01.600
[Guest]: Better not say that because that's a minefield, better to be safe.

00:41:01.600 --> 00:41:05.160
[Guest]: And what that does is it destroys discourse.

00:41:05.160 --> 00:41:12.280
[Guest]: It destroys conversation, kind of like, just to be, this is a crude stereotype, probably

00:41:12.280 --> 00:41:13.840
[Guest]: shouldn't say it.

00:41:13.840 --> 00:41:17.360
[Guest]: Stereotypes are troubling, you get in trouble for stereotypes, but I'll use the difference

00:41:17.360 --> 00:41:25.000
[Guest]: between, say, a stereotypical upper class British gentleman and somebody from, let's

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:31.880
[Guest]: call it a Mediterranean culture, could be Israel or Greece or Italy.

00:41:31.880 --> 00:41:40.000
[Guest]: So in the British salon, drawing room, certain things aren't talked about.

00:41:40.000 --> 00:41:43.080
[Guest]: Certain emotions are not expressed.

00:41:43.080 --> 00:41:46.720
[Guest]: Everything is a bit restrained.

00:41:46.720 --> 00:41:49.040
[Guest]: Could even say it's civilized.

00:41:49.040 --> 00:41:52.120
[Guest]: In the Mediterranean culture, everything's out on the table.

00:41:52.120 --> 00:41:56.360
[Guest]: People are yelling at each other, calling each other names sometimes.

00:41:56.360 --> 00:41:59.000
[Guest]: Now those are two different ways of living.

00:41:59.000 --> 00:42:06.120
[Guest]: I think there's some middle path that's the right path where you have an authentic conversation,

00:42:06.120 --> 00:42:11.520
[Guest]: but you don't necessarily tell somebody everything you're thinking.

00:42:11.520 --> 00:42:14.240
[Guest]: That I think does require some forms of restraint.

00:42:14.240 --> 00:42:18.960
[Guest]: But if you go too far in either direction, you're going to destroy the opportunity to

00:42:18.960 --> 00:42:19.960
[Guest]: learn.

00:42:19.960 --> 00:42:22.960
[Guest]: You're going to destroy the opportunity to live vividly.

00:42:22.960 --> 00:42:28.000
[Guest]: So I feel like we're heading, certainly in academic life in America, we're heading toward

00:42:28.000 --> 00:42:32.320
[Guest]: a world where a bunch of things are not on the table and it can't be talked about.

00:42:32.320 --> 00:42:37.240
[Guest]: In fact, I just saw somebody tweeted this morning that if there are any differences

00:42:37.240 --> 00:42:40.760
[Guest]: between groups, that's racism.

00:42:40.760 --> 00:42:41.760
[Guest]: It's all because of racism.

00:42:41.760 --> 00:42:42.760
[Guest]: It can't be anything else.

00:42:42.760 --> 00:42:48.880
[Guest]: If you see statistical differences by race, all of it's racism.

00:42:48.880 --> 00:42:54.000
[Guest]: So that's a beautiful example, tragic example of what we're talking about earlier with the

00:42:54.000 --> 00:42:55.560
[Guest]: blind spot.

00:42:55.560 --> 00:43:00.960
[Guest]: And somebody, you know, responded like, what, I mean, there's no agency, there's no ability.

00:43:00.960 --> 00:43:02.880
[Guest]: Nobody has any responsibility.

00:43:02.880 --> 00:43:04.120
[Guest]: Everything is a result of other people.

00:43:04.120 --> 00:43:07.840
[Guest]: I mean, if you think about that, ultimately that's dehumanizing the people you're supposedly

00:43:07.840 --> 00:43:09.560
[Guest]: caring about.

00:43:09.560 --> 00:43:11.040
[Guest]: But that's where we're going.

00:43:11.040 --> 00:43:15.280
[Guest]: If we're not careful, we're going to head to a world where you can't raise those other

00:43:15.280 --> 00:43:16.280
[Guest]: possible explanations.

00:43:16.280 --> 00:43:19.440
[Guest]: And once you do that, you stop learning.

00:43:19.440 --> 00:43:20.440
[Guest]: You're in religion.

00:43:20.440 --> 00:43:21.440
[Guest]: I like religion, by the way.

00:43:21.440 --> 00:43:23.480
[Guest]: You probably know I'm a religious person.

00:43:23.480 --> 00:43:24.480
[Guest]: I'm Jewish.

00:43:24.480 --> 00:43:25.480
[Guest]: I think religion is great.

00:43:25.480 --> 00:43:26.480
[Guest]: I'm a big fan of it.

00:43:26.480 --> 00:43:31.240
[Guest]: I think it helps you organize your life and it's powerful and it gives meaning.

00:43:31.240 --> 00:43:33.680
[Guest]: And I like religion a lot.

00:43:33.680 --> 00:43:37.840
[Guest]: I don't think it belongs in academic life.

00:43:37.840 --> 00:43:39.820
[Guest]: That needs, that's supposed to be something different.

00:43:39.820 --> 00:43:44.280
[Guest]: And as it tends toward religion, I think we're heading toward a world where knowledge is

00:43:44.280 --> 00:43:46.320
[Guest]: not going to be created.

00:43:46.320 --> 00:43:47.880
[Guest]: We're just going to have priesthoods.

00:43:47.880 --> 00:43:48.880
[Amit Varma]: That's not good.

00:43:48.880 --> 00:43:49.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:43:49.880 --> 00:43:53.080
[Amit Varma]: And I also do this weekly Econ podcast called Econ Central.

00:43:53.080 --> 00:43:54.720
[Amit Varma]: I co-host it with a friend.

00:43:54.720 --> 00:43:59.560
[Amit Varma]: And our latest episode we just dropped today, we are recording this on July 16th, is called

00:43:59.560 --> 00:44:03.240
[Amit Varma]: The Economics of the Chilling Effect, where, you know, we speak about exactly what you

00:44:03.240 --> 00:44:07.880
[Amit Varma]: just spoke about, that, you know, the incentives are now aligned for people to shut up.

00:44:07.880 --> 00:44:13.080
[Amit Varma]: So there might be a silent majority that disagrees with the vocal minority, but oh my God, you're

00:44:13.080 --> 00:44:18.120
[Amit Varma]: not going to speak out because why, you know, invite the mob upon yourself, which is, you

00:44:18.120 --> 00:44:21.480
[Amit Varma]: know, incredibly worrying for our discourse.

00:44:21.480 --> 00:44:23.240
[Amit Varma]: We'll take a quick commercial break now.

00:44:23.240 --> 00:44:27.800
[Amit Varma]: And I'm looking forward to continuing this conversation when we come back.

00:44:27.800 --> 00:44:29.000
[Amit Varma]: Great.

